node.text:
"Last month, at a pediatrician appointment for Sunday, I was handed an iPad-like device and asked to respond on a scale of 1 to 10 to prompts such as: ‘In the past seven days, I have been able to laugh and see the funny side of things,’ and ‘I have been anxious or worried for no good reason.’⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
The questionnaire is part of the Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale, used to detect postpartum depression. A score of 10 or higher, or a positive answer to question #10 — ‘The thought of harming myself has occurred to me’ — is suggestive of postpartum depression, while women who score above 13 are likely suffering from a depressive illness.⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends screening all women at least once for #depression and #anxiety during the #perinatal period.⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
It feels impersonal, but screenings are important. They can save lives.⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
Amid reports that 15 to 20 percent of women experience a perinatal mood disorder during #pregnancy or #postpartum, what often goes unreported is this: Suicide is a leading cause of death in the postpartum period.⁣ 💔⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
Read that again. ⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
Moms are often left out of the suicide conversation. ⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
In my latest for Instyle Magazine, I report on this (sometimes silent) issue.⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
As Margaret G. Spinelli, M.D., a clinical professor of psychiatry at Columbia University told me, in the 1980s you could find physicians in this country telling women that their mood was “protected” during pregnancy + postpartum (it’s not). ⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
In fact, she had to do some of her education in London because, as she puts it, “there was no such thing as ‘perinatal psychiatry’ in the United States.”⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
Today, there is still more that needs to be done to get pregnant women and new moms the mental health resources they need but experts emphatically agree on this: Maternal death by suicide IS preventable. ⁣⁠⠀
⁣⁠⠀
Talking about it is important. So is asking your new mom friends if they’re okay if you suspect they’re down. ⁣❤️”⁠⠀
⁠⠀
⁠⠀
⁣Words: @dearsundaymotherhood⁠⠀
Art: @morganharpernichols

⁠"🧡Mamas, I wanna know how long did you breastfeed? Or currently breastfeeding?🧡⁠
⠀⁠
As we are still celebrating #blackbreastfeeding week, I wanna share some facts with you that I’ve learned from @itstashhaynes & BlackBreastfeedingweek.org. THIS IS WHY this week is needed.⁠
⠀⁠
1. The high black infant mortality rate⁠
⠀⁠
According to the CDC, increased breastfeeding among black women could decrease infant mortality rates by as much as 50%.⁠
⠀⁠
2. High rates of diet-related disease⁠
⠀⁠
From upper respiratory infections and Type II diabetes to asthma, Sudden Infant Death Syndrome and childhood obesity—these issues are rampant in our communities. And breast milk is the best preventative medicine nature provides.⁠
⠀⁠
3. Lack of diversity in lactation field⁠
⠀⁠
There is a blatant disparity in breastfeeding leadership as well. It is not debatable that breastfeeding advocacy is white female-led. So many of the lactation professionals, though well-intentioned, are not culturally competent, sensitive or relevant enough to properly deal with African American moms.⁠
⠀⁠
4. Unique cultural barriers among black women⁠
⠀⁠
From our role as wet nurses in slavery being forced to breastfeed and nurture our slave owners children often to the detriment of our children, to the lack of mainstream role models and multi-generational support , to our own stereotyping within our community.⁠
⠀⁠
5. Desert-Like Conditions in Our Communities:⁠
⠀⁠
There’s a major lack of support in urban areas to help moms become educated when it comes to breastfeeding. Instead they are targeted with formula campaigns more than any other ethnicity."⁠
⁠
⁠
🎥Video & words @sopharush

every year we “celebrate” National Rainbow Baby Day and every year i forget how this day truly impacts me. 

because the thing is... although we are celebrating our miracle babies, we also have to acknowledge the pain, loss, and grief of the baby(s) we have lost. 

sometimes it feels like that part gets lost. 

so, as we talk about this day, don’t forget to also talk about the loss, along with the miracles. 

and please don’t forget to also acknowledge those who are still waiting for their rainbow baby too. 

head to stories, to hear more about this and to hear my personal journey....

⁠
📷 @rebornfromwithin⁠

“I don’t know who needs to hear this but here we go 😊⁣⁠
⁣⁠
No matter your reason for choosing to pump and provide your child with nature’s milk! Do you!!! ⁣⁠
⁣⁠
While you’re at it, pat yourself on the back. No one needs to know why you choose to pump, but I’m here to tell you that pumping is breastfeeding too! ⁣⁠
⁠
I don't know who needs to hear this, but... Pumping Is Still Breastfeeding. ⁠
⁠
Just you're friendly loving reminder. ⁠"⁠
⁣⁠
⁠
📷 @abirthtoremember⁠
⁠
⁠
[Image ID - illustration of woman on a pink background wearing a breast pump with a blue shirt and black pants while scrolling her phone with the words "Pumping Is Still Breastfeeding written next to her]
